WATER’S NOT WET! And I’ll tell you why. To say that something is wet means that the water on the surface of that something can be removed. You get caught outside in the rain, you say “Aw, my hair got wet, now I gotta get it redid.” “Aw, my shoes got wet, now I gotta let’em sit outside, and dry.” You don’t say, that the ocean gets wet, it’s just water, water is water. Ladies and gentlemen, here’s the simple proof test: This counter is dry, I pour water on it, it becomes wet. Can it be dried? Absolutely. Therefore was wet it is now dry. self-insert protagonists aren't always a bad thing inherently anon, they're stereotyped as bad because a blank slate nice type is really easy to write for. However, that doesn't necessarily mean that a self-insert protagonist has to be a blank slate, all they have to be are relatable enough for the target audience for them to "self insert into" you see this a lot with YA protags like harry potter and Percy Jackson, which have strong defined personalities but are relateable enough for the reader to self insert into. In this thread's case, the average self insert protag is just seen as a pretty normal everyman type character, which while bland doesn't really need to be anything else.
Tl;dr: self insert in of itself aren't bad things, like anything in writing there are good and bad ways to write them
